EIS 34[bold]Written evidence submitted by Shell International Ltd[bold]What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK? [bold]Shell has had a home in the UK since the founding of Shell Transport and Trading in 1897. As the UK’s largest listed company, Shell makes a major contribution to the UK, not just through delivering energy and providing products and services to our customer
[normal]s, but also through employment, tax revenues and investment, which boosts the economy. Approximately £1 out of every £10 of all dividends paid in the FTSE 100 last year came from Shell. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In conjunction with its co-
[normal]ventures
[normal], Shell operates around 12% of 
[normal]the UK’s production of oil and gas and invests around $2bn per annum in the North Sea. Shell has played a significant role in diversifying UK gas supply through the operation of an infrastructure that processes 35% of the gas coming into the UK. In additio
[normal]n to developing our assets in the North Sea
[normal],
[normal] Shell is working on several projects in the UK, including: the first full scale gas power Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) project at the Peterhead power station; a new fuel import terminal at Coryton in Essex a
[normal]nd our investment in and successful integration of 250 recently acquired new petrol stations. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Shell has a long history of supporting the UK’s highly developed oil and gas supply chains demonstrated by an extensive number of partnerships with UK compan
[normal]ies on our projects throughout the world as seen in the examples
[normal] below
[normal]. 
[normal]Around 80-85% of the exploration and production spend for Shell U.K. Ltd
[normal] 
[normal]is placed with UK companies.
[normal] 
[normal]For instance, 
[normal]around 500 million $ of 
[normal]the 
[normal]Majnoon
[normal] project in Iraq is to UK companies.
[normal] In addition, UK companies attract a significant amount of work from other Shell exploration and production operations such as the Netherlands and Norway, where
[normal] 
[normal]respectively approximately 10% and 15% of ann
[normal]ual spend goes
[normal] 
[normal]to UK suppliers.
